  "prompt": "What are some examples of player coming out of retirement after a long time?",
  "response": "There have been several notable instances of athletes coming out of retirement after a long period. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Michael Jordan**: One of the most famous cases, Michael Jordan retired from basketball for the first time in 1993 to pursue a career in baseball. He returned to the NBA in 1995, leading the Chicago Bulls to three more championships. Jordan retired again in 1999, but came back to play for the Washington Wizards in 2001 before retiring for good in 2003.\n\n2. **George Foreman**: The former heavyweight boxing champion initially retired in 1977 but made a surprising comeback a decade later in 1987. Foreman went on to regain the heavyweight title in 1994 at the age of 45, becoming the oldest heavyweight champion in history.\n\n3. **Roger Clemens**: The Major League Baseball pitcher retired in 2003 but made multiple comebacks, including returning to play for the Houston Astros in 2004 and later for the New York Yankees in 2007.\n\n4. **Brett Favre**: The legendary NFL quarterback retired multiple times. He first retired in 2008 but returned to play for the New York Jets and later the Minnesota Vikings before retiring for good in 2010.\n\n5. **Mario Lemieux**: The NHL star retired from professional hockey in 1997 due to health issues but made a successful return to the Pittsburgh Penguins in 2000, continuing to play until retiring again in 2006.\n\n6. **Martina Hingis**: The tennis champion retired in 2002 due to injuries but made multiple comebacks, including returning in 2006 and then again in 2013 to play doubles, achieving significant success in her later career.\n\nThese athletes have demonstrated the unique ability to return to high-level competition after a prolonged absence, often achieving remarkable success in their comebacks.",
